To analyze the Swedish sentence and produce a dependency tree, we first identify the tokens and their relationships. The sentence is:

”Den gamle fiskaren är smärtsamt medveten om att han har hamnat i en omöjlig situation.”

The tokenization is as follows: 
1. Den
2. gamle
3. fiskaren
4. är
5. smärtsamt
6. medveten
7. om
8. att
9. han
10. har
11. hamnat
12. i
13. en
14. omöjlig
15. situation
16. .

Now, we can analyze the dependencies:
- "är" (is) functions as the main verb and is the root of the sentence (head of the clause).
- "Den gamle fiskaren" (the old fisherman) is the subject of the verb "är".
- "smärtsamt medveten" (painfully aware) describes the subject and is part of the predicate.
- "om att han har hamnat i en omöjlig situation" (about that he has ended up in an impossible situation) is a complement of "medveten".
- Within this complement, "han" is the subject of "har hamnat" (has ended up), and "i en omöjlig situation" is a prepositional phrase where "i" (in) governs "situation".

The resulting dependency tree representation is:

```
[(1, Den, 3), 
 (2, gamle, 3), 
 (3, fiskaren, 4), 
 (4, är, 0), 
 (5, smärtsamt, 6), 
 (6, medveten, 4), 
 (7, om, 6), 
 (8, att, 7), 
 (9, han, 10), 
 (10, har, 11), 
 (11, hamnat, 12), 
 (12, i, 11), 
 (13, en, 14), 
 (14, omöjlig, 15), 
 (15, situation, 12), 
 (16, ., 4)]
```

This captures the token indices, the tokens, and their heads correctly according to the dependencies present in the Swedish sentence.